Predict Bike Sharing Demand with AutoGluon Template¶

Project: Predict Bike Sharing Demand with AutoGluon¶

This notebook is a template with each step that you need to complete for the project.

Please fill in your code where there are explicit ? markers in the notebook. You are welcome to add more cells and code as you see fit.

Once you have completed all the code implementations, please export your notebook as a HTML file so the reviews can view your code. Make sure you have all outputs correctly outputted.

File-> Export Notebook As... -> Export Notebook as HTML

There is a writeup to complete as well after all code implememtation is done. Please answer all questions and attach the necessary tables and charts. You can complete the writeup in either markdown or PDF.

Completing the code template and writeup template will cover all of the rubric points for this project.

The rubric contains "Stand Out Suggestions" for enhancing the project beyond the minimum requirements. The stand out suggestions are optional. If you decide to pursue the "stand out suggestions", you can include the code in this notebook and also discuss the results in the writeup file.

Step 1: Create an account with Kaggle¶

Create Kaggle Account and download API key¶

Below is example of steps to get the API username and key. Each student will have their own username and key.

  1. Open account settings.
  2. Scroll down to API and click Create New API Token.
  3. Open up kaggle.json and use the username and key.

Step 2: Download the Kaggle dataset using the kaggle python library¶

Open up Sagemaker Studio and use starter template¶

  1. Notebook should be using a ml.t3.medium instance (2 vCPU + 4 GiB)
  2. Notebook should be using kernal: Python 3 (MXNet 1.8 Python 3.7 CPU Optimized)

Step 3: Train a model using AutoGluon’s Tabular Prediction¶

Requirements:

  • We are prediting count, so it is the label we are setting.
  • Ignore casual and registered columns as they are also not present in the test dataset.
  • Use the root_mean_squared_error as the metric to use for evaluation.
  • Set a time limit of 10 minutes (600 seconds).
  • Use the preset best_quality to focus on creating the best model.
In [12]:
predictor = TabularPredictor(
    label = 'count'
    , eval_metric = 'root_mean_squared_error'
).fit(
    train_data = train.drop(columns = ['casual', 'registered'])
    ,time_limit = 600
    , presets = 'best_quality'
)

Step 4: Exploratory Data Analysis and Creating an additional feature¶

  • Any additional feature will do, but a great suggestion would be to separate out the datetime into hour, day, or month parts.

In [11]:
# create a new feature
train['month'] = train['datetime'].dt.month
train['hour'] = train['datetime'].dt.hour
train['day'] = train['datetime'].dt.day

train.loc[(train['hour'] < 7) | (train['hour'] > 19), 'workinghours'] = 0
train.loc[(train['hour'] >= 7) & (train['hour'] <= 19), 'workinghours'] = 1
train['workingdayhour'] = (train['workingday'].astype(str) + train['workinghours'].astype(str))
In [12]:
# create a new feature
test['month'] = test['datetime'].dt.month
test['hour'] = test['datetime'].dt.hour
test['day'] = test['datetime'].dt.day

test.loc[(train['hour'] < 7) | (test['hour'] > 19), 'workinghours'] = 0
test.loc[(train['hour'] >= 7) | (test['hour'] <= 19), 'workinghours'] = 1
test['workingdayhour'] = (test['workingday'].astype(str) + test['workinghours'].astype(str))

Make category types for these so models know they are not just numbers¶

  • AutoGluon originally sees these as ints, but in reality they are int representations of a category.
  • Setting the dtype to category will classify these as categories in AutoGluon.
In [13]:
from pandas.api.types import CategoricalDtype

train["season"] = train['season'].astype('category')
train["weather"] = train['weather'].astype('category')
train["holiday"] = train['holiday'].astype('category')
train["workingday"] = train['workingday'].astype('category')
train["workinghours"] = train['workinghours'].astype('category')

train['hour'] = train['hour'].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=train['hour'].sort_values().unique(), ordered=True))
train['day'] = train['day'].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=train['day'].sort_values().unique(), ordered=True))
train['month'] = train['month'].astype(CategoricalDtype(categories=train['month'].sort_values().unique(), ordered=True))

train['workingdayhour'] = train['workingdayhour'].astype('category')
In [14]:
test["season"] = test['season'].astype('category')
test["weather"] = test['weather'].astype('category')
test["holiday"] = test['holiday'].astype('category')
test["workingday"] = test['workingday'].astype('category')
test["workinghours"] = test['workinghours'].astype('category')

Step 6: Hyper parameter optimization¶

  • There are many options for hyper parameter optimization.
  • Options are to change the AutoGluon higher level parameters or the individual model hyperparameters.
  • The hyperparameters of the models themselves that are in AutoGluon. Those need the hyperparameter and hyperparameter_tune_kwargs arguments.
In [51]:
# hyperparam options taken from https://auto.gluon.ai/stable/tutorials/tabular_prediction/tabular-indepth.html
import autogluon.core as ag

time_limit = 2*60  # train various models for ~2 min
num_trials = 5  # try at most 5 different hyperparameter configurations for each type of model
search_strategy = 'auto'  # to tune hyperparameters using random search routine with a local scheduler

hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = {  # HPO is not performed unless hyperparameter_tune_kwargs is specified
    'num_trials': num_trials,
    'scheduler' : 'local',
    'searcher': search_strategy,
}

gbm_options = {  
    'num_boost_round': 100, 
    'num_leaves': ag.space.Int(lower=26, upper=66, default=36)
}

hyperparameters = { 
    'GBM': gbm_options
} 

predictor_new_hpo = TabularPredictor(
    label = 'count'
    , eval_metric = 'root_mean_squared_error'
).fit(
    train_data = train.drop(columns = ['casual', 'registered'])
    , time_limit = 600
    , presets = 'best_quality'
    , hyperparameters = hyperparameters
    , hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = hyperparameter_tune_kwargs
)

# hyperparam options taken from https://auto.gluon.ai/stable/tutorials/tabular_prediction/tabular-indepth.html
import autogluon.core as ag

time_limit = 2*60  # train various models for ~2 min
num_trials = 5  # try at most 5 different hyperparameter configurations for each type of model
search_strategy = 'auto'  # to tune hyperparameters using random search routine with a local scheduler

hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = {  # HPO is not performed unless hyperparameter_tune_kwargs is specified
    'num_trials': num_trials,
    'scheduler' : 'local',
    'searcher': search_strategy,
}

gbm_options = {  
    'num_boost_round': 100, 
    'num_leaves': ag.space.Int(lower=26, upper=66, default=36)
}

nn_options = {  # specifies non-default hyperparameter values for neural network model
    'num_epochs': 10,  # number of training epochs (controls training time of NN models)
    'learning_rate': ag.space.Real(1e-4, 1e-2, default=5e-4, log=True),  # learning rate used in training (real-valued hyperparameter searched on log-scale)
    'activation': ag.space.Categorical('relu', 'softrelu', 'tanh'),  # activation function used in NN (categorical hyperparameter, default = first entry)
    'dropout_prob': ag.space.Real(0.0, 0.5, default=0.1),  # dropout probability (real-valued hyperparameter)
}

hyperparameters = { 
    'GBM': gbm_options
    ,'NN_TORCH': nn_options
} 

predictor_new_hpo_incl_nn = TabularPredictor(
    label = 'count'
    , eval_metric = 'root_mean_squared_error'
).fit(
    train_data = train.drop(columns = ['casual', 'registered'])
    , time_limit = 600
    , presets = 'best_quality'
    , hyperparameters = hyperparameters
    , hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = hyperparameter_tune_kwargs
)

Lets try with those hyperparameters and also incorporating bagging and stack-ensembling¶

This might not lead to any changes as when presets = 'best_quality' (as we've been using) the auto_stack argument, which finds bag/stack values for you, gets set to true.

In [35]:
# hyperparam options taken from https://auto.gluon.ai/stable/tutorials/tabular_prediction/tabular-indepth.html
import autogluon.core as ag

time_limit = 2*60  # train various models for ~2 min
num_trials = 5  # try at most 5 different hyperparameter configurations for each type of model
search_strategy = 'auto'  # to tune hyperparameters using random search routine with a local scheduler

hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = {  # HPO is not performed unless hyperparameter_tune_kwargs is specified
    'num_trials': num_trials,
    'scheduler' : 'local',
    'searcher': search_strategy,
}

gbm_options = {  
    'num_boost_round': 100, 
    'num_leaves': ag.space.Int(lower=26, upper=66, default=36)
}

nn_options = {  # specifies non-default hyperparameter values for neural network model
    'num_epochs': 10,  # number of training epochs (controls training time of NN models)
    'learning_rate': ag.space.Real(1e-4, 1e-2, default=5e-4, log=True),  # learning rate used in training (real-valued hyperparameter searched on log-scale)
    'activation': ag.space.Categorical('relu', 'softrelu', 'tanh'),  # activation function used in NN (categorical hyperparameter, default = first entry)
    'dropout_prob': ag.space.Real(0.0, 0.5, default=0.1),  # dropout probability (real-valued hyperparameter)
}

hyperparameters = { 
    'GBM': gbm_options
    ,'NN_TORCH': nn_options
} 

predictor_new_hpo_stack_bag = TabularPredictor(
    label = 'count'
    , eval_metric = 'root_mean_squared_error'
).fit(
    train_data = train.drop(columns = ['casual', 'registered'])
    , num_bag_folds=5
    , num_bag_sets=1
    , num_stack_levels=1
    , time_limit = 600
    , presets = 'best_quality'
    , hyperparameters = hyperparameters
    , hyperparameter_tune_kwargs = hyperparameter_tune_kwargs
)
